	<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/24/morning-agenda-monitor-for-credit-suisse-named/" data-title="Morning Agenda: Monitor for Credit Suisse Named" data-description="A regulator is close to picking a corporate monitor for Credit Suisse. | The dismissal of American Apparel&#039;s chief raises corporate-governance questions. | The Supreme Court erects new hurdles to class actions for securities fraud. | Three traders leave Steven A. Cohen&#039;s family office.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="round-up">
<div class="ru-top-story">
<h6 class="kicker"></h6>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Neil Barofsky, an old foe of the 2008 bank bailouts, has managed to secure a familiar role: watchdog for one of the worldâs biggest banks, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/23/neil-barofsky-ex-prosecutor-and-old-foe-said-to-be-monitor-for-credit-suisse">Ben Protess and Jessica Silver-Greenberg write in DealBook</a></b>. New York Stateâs financial regulator is said to be close to picking Mr. Barofsky, a former federal prosecutor, as the corporate monitor for Credit Suisse after the bankâs guilty plea to helping American clients evade taxes. Credit Suisse agreed to hire a monitor as part of a related settlement. Separately, <b>a monitor was also installed late last year at BNP Paribas</b>, the giant French bank suspected of violating sanctions provisions.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The government has awarded more than half of corporate monitor positions to former federal prosecutors, who have embraced the role as a blend of prosecutorial pursuit and the law firm billable hour. Monitors are <b>chosen to act as the governmentâs post-settlement proxy</b>, shining a light on the inner workings of corporations and suggesting steps to bolster compliance procedures. But the monitors themselves <b>often operate in secret</b>, routinely sealing the results of their investigations and answering to companies and regulators but not to a judge.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The monitoring process has drawn criticism from Benjamin M. Lawsky, who heads the New York regulator. In particular, Mr. Lawsky has attacked the inherent conflict that arises when banks pay their own monitors, whose fees often run in the millions of dollars. Still, prosecutors and regulators have been criticized for <b>steering monitor jobs to friends and former colleagues</b>. In this case, Mr. Lawsky and Mr. Barofsky worked together as federal prosecutors in Manhattan and remain friends. To avoid the appearance of a conflict, Mr. Lawsky has recused himself from the selection of monitors.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">QUESTIONS AFTER OUSTING OF AMERICAN APPAREL CHIEF <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> The dismissal last week of Dov Charney, the founder of American Apparel, âraises all sorts of thorny corporate-governance questions for investors and boards about iconic â and notorious â leaders, especially in creative fields,â<b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/23/when-a-founder-misbehaves"> Andrew Ross Sorkin writes in the DealBook column</a></b>. âCorporate America is filled with examples of chief executives and founders who stepped down after proof, or even suggestions, of impropriety. Some are fired quickly when investors and boards are alerted. But others, like Mr. Charney, are allowed to linger in their roles for years.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âOften, as now appears to be the case with Mr. Charney, a board becomes so convinced that the company is wrapped up in a founderâs personal image that it is <b>slow to replace the chief when necessary</b>. It fears that the firing will upend the companyâs image or culture and cause other key employees to leave out of loyalty,â Mr. Sorkin writes. And in Mr. Charneyâs case, his control of 27 percent of the company may have made it even harder for the board to oust him. But, Mr. Sorkin writes, âthe situation changes when the image of the brand becomes tarnished and it <b>starts to cost shareholders money</b>.â Mr. Charney <b><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/06/24/business/ousted-american-apparel-chief-fighting-back.html">filed a formal notice</a></b> on Monday indicating that he did not plan to leave quietly.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">NEW HURDLE IN SECURITIES CLASS ACTIONS <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> The Supreme Court on Monday made it harder for investors to band together to pursue claims that they were misled when they bought or sold securities. But the justices did not accept a broader challenge, one that could have put an end to most class actions for securities fraud, <b><a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/06/24/business/Justices-rule-on-class-actions-for-securities-fraud.html?ref=business">Adam Liptak writes in The New York Times</a></b>. Chief Justice John G. Roberts Jr., writing for the majority in a unanimous decision that split 6 to 3 on its rationales, said defendants facing class actions might try to show at an early stage that their statements did not affect their securitiesâ market price.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The decision, in a case involving the oil services company Halliburton, will let corporate defendants defeat some securities fraud claims at the outset but did <b>not go as far as some business groups hoped</b>. Still, the ruling will cut back on suits that can involve enormous sums.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe opinion shows that the Supreme Court seems to love to tinker with the securities laws, but it continues to refuse to kill the business,â <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/23/tinkering-with-securities-class-actions/?">Steven M. Davidoff writes in the Deal Professor column</a></b>. âAll told, it means <b>securities fraud suits are like cockroaches</b>: hard to kill.â</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title">ON THE AGENDA <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> <b>Big day for economic data</b>: The Federal Housing Finance Agency <b>house price index</b> for April is out at 9 a.m. The Standard &#038; Poorâs/Case-Shiller <b>home price index</b> for April is released at 9 a.m. Data on <b>new home sales</b> is out at 10 a.m. The <b>consumer confidence index</b> is out at 10 a.m.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>Charles I. Plosser</b>, president of the Philadelphia Fed, gives a speech at 8:05 a.m. in New York on the economy and monetary policy. <b>William C. Dudley</b>, president of the New York Fed, gives a speech at 2 p.m. in San Juan, Puerto Rico. <b>John C. Williams</b>, president of the San Francisco Fed, gives a speech at 6:30 p.m. at Stanford on the global economy.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>On the Hill</b>: The House <b>Committee on Financial Services</b> holds a hearing at 10 a.m. entitled âThe Annual Report of the Financial Stability Oversight Council.â The Senate <b>Committee on Finance</b> holds a hearing at 10 a.m. on student debt. The House <b>Subcommittee on Regulatory Reform, Commercial and Antitrust Law</b> holds a hearing at 10:30 a.m. on the proposed merger of AT&#038;T and DirecTV.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><b>World Cup watch</b>: <b>Costa Rica vs. England</b> at noon. <b>Italy at Uruguay</b> at noon. <b>Greece at Ivory Coast</b> at 4 p.m. <b>Japan at Colombia</b> at 4 p.m.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story --></p>
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"> 3 LEAVE COHENâS POINT72 <span class="divider">Â |Â </span></span><!-- end .title --> Over the last week, three technology stock traders have left Point72 Asset Management, the nearly $10 billion family office of Steven A. Cohen, in a new round of defections at a firm that is still dealing with the fallout from a significant insider trading investigation, <b><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/23/three-traders-leave-steven-cohens-office-in-boston">DealBookâs Matthew Goldstein writes</a></b>. All three traders â Telis Bertsekas, Michael Valentine and Nina Hughes â had worked in the relatively small Boston office of the 850-employee firm, which maintains its headquarters in Stamford, Conn.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The departures of Mr. Bertsekas and Ms. Hughes are notable because the two jointly managed a portfolio with a value of several hundred million dollars. Ms. Hughes was <b>one of the few women to work as a portfolio manager</b> for Mr. Cohen. It is not clear where the three traders are going. Mr. Cohen has made a <b>number of moves to slow departures from his firm</b>, including pressing portfolio managers to sign contracts that would bind them to their jobs until the end of 2016.</p>
</div>
